@node Top
@top Nytrix

Nytrix uses explicit imports, native output, compile-time source generation,
and direct C ABI interop. The Markdown docs in @file{docs/spec/} are the
canonical language reference; this manual is the compact Info entry point.

@menu
* Model::      Source units, values, execution, imports.
* Syntax::     Core source spellings.
* Native::     Layouts, externs, headers, pointers, handles.
* Runtime::    Safety, ownership, cleanup, async.
* Tooling::    Commands and documentation.
* See Also::   Repository docs.
@end menu

@node Model
@chapter Model

A source unit is a UTF-8 file containing imports, declarations, modules, and
statements. There is no implicit prelude. Names enter scope through @code{use}.
Top-level statements run when a file is executed. @code{module} controls the
exported surface.

@example
use std.core

module sample(add)

fn add(int a, int b) int @{
   a + b
@}

#main @{
   assert_eq(add(1, 2), 3, "add")
@}
@end example

@code{#main @{ ... @}} runs only for the direct entry file. Imported modules
skip it.

Execution modes are:

@table @code
@item ny file.ny
JIT run one file.
@item ny -c 'source'
Run inline source.
@item ny -run file.ny
Build and run a temporary native executable.
@item ny -o app file.ny
Emit a native executable.
@item ny, ny -i, ny --plain-repl
Open the REPL.
@end table

@node Syntax
@chapter Syntax

@section Bindings And Functions

@example
def name = expr
mut name = expr
def Type name = expr
mut Type name = expr
def a, b = expr

fn name(params) @{ body @}
fn name(params) Type @{ body @}
fn(v)@{ expr @}
@end example

Function parameters, typed bindings, and fields use @code{Type name}. @code{fn(...)} is the canonical inline callable spelling.

@section Types

@example
T
T<A>
T<A, B>
?T
*T
fnptr
seq | sequence
numeric
indexable
iterable
allocator
handle
@end example

Common forms are @code{list<int>}, @code{dict<str, int>},
@code{Result<T, E>}, and ADTs such as @code{Option<int>}.

@section Control

@example
if(cond)@{ body @} elif(other)@{ body @} else @{ body @}
while(cond)@{ body @}
for value, index in expr @{ body @}
case value @{ literal -> expr _ -> fallback @}
match value @{ Pattern(value) -> expr _ -> fallback @}
try @{ body @} catch err @{ handler @}
defer @{ cleanup @}
with Type: name = value @{ body @}
@end example

@section Compile Time

@example
comptime @{ body @}
comptime table Name @{ pattern -> value @}
comptime match Name(key, fallback)
comptime template name(args) @{ declarations @}
comptime emit name(args)
assert_compile(cond, "message")
assert_compile_range(value, lo, hi, "message")
assert_compile_index(container, index, "message")
@end example

Generated modules use @code{module pkg.name generated from Spec @{ ... @}}.
Platform guards include @code{#linux}, @code{#macos}, @code{#windows}, and
@code{#if(expr)}.

@node Native
@chapter Native

Native boundaries use layouts, externs, header imports, pointers, handles, and
explicit ownership.

@example
#include <stdlib.h> as "c"
#include "./header.h" as ""

extern "library" @{ fn symbol(Type arg) Type @}
extern @{ fn process_symbol(Type arg) Type @}

layout Pixel @{
   u8 r,
   u8 g,
   u8 b,
   u8 a
@}
@end example

@code{handle} is an opaque native scalar. A handle is not pointer-addressable
unless the native API says so. Use @code{*T}, @code{ptr}, @code{load*_h}, and
@code{store*_h} at pointer/handle boundaries.

@node Runtime
@chapter Runtime

Ordinary values are runtime-managed. Raw pointers, handles, layouts, and FFI
strings cross into native lifetime rules.

@table @code
@item --strict-types
Keep default compile-time type checks enabled.
@item --borrow-check --ownership-strict
Check moves, borrows, releases, and ownership returns.
@item --safe-mode
Use default type checks plus ownership/borrow checks, RC/RAII cleanup, strict
effect/alias policy, and raw-memory diagnostics.
@item --heap=gc
Use the opt-in runtime collector.
@end table

Ownership helpers include @code{borrow(x)}, @code{&x}, @code{own(x)},
@code{release(x)}, and @code{forget(x)}. Cleanup forms are @code{defer} and
@code{with}.

Async and concurrency live in the standard library: stackless async tasks, OS
threads, atomics, queues, channels, sockets, and process tubes.

@node Tooling
@chapter Tooling

@example
ny doc search json
ny doc search --symbols recvuntil
ny doc get std.math.parse.data.json
ny fmt --check file.ny
ny fmt --trim --check file.ny
ny test --pattern name
ny perf
@end example

Use generated docs for signatures and exported names. Use spec pages for exact
language rules.

